&#xa0;
[normal]Written evidence from J M Beaumont[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Evidence to your Committee by Lord McNally Tuesday 5[bold]th[bold] November[bold]&#xa0;[bold]I have been listening to the archive recording of the meeting of your committee on Friday 5
[normal]th
[normal] November 2013 and wish to put before you facts about 
[normal]Sark
[normal] that were not brought out by Lord McNally.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Lord McNally suggests that the lack of cooperation between Chief Pleas and the Barclays is a fault on both sides.  I certainly do not see it that way and to back up my assertion I enclose just two instances where perfectly reasonable requests from a committee of Chief Pleas to Mr Delaney of 
[normal]Sark
[normal] Developments Ltd and the replies they received.  In one case ignoring the request made and the second the reply was just a rant against Chief Pleas and its members, unfounded accusations, and with no attempt to answer the request made.  These are typical and inhibit Chief Pleas from trying to get a dialog going.  It takes two to Tango.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]There is truth in Lord McNally’s assertion that 
[normal]Sark
[normal] currently lacks leadership, however this is in no small measure due to the continuous vitriolic attacks in the 
[normal]Sark
[normal] Newsletter.  Our Principle leader and Chair of our lead committee, Mr. Charles Maitland resigned as he and his wife found the constant abuse more than they should be asked to bear and to date Chief Pleas have failed to find a replacement.  Another and perhaps more sinister development is the resignation of our recently appointed 
[normal]Vingtenier
[normal] (Second in command Constable) who worked for Kevin Delaney of 
[normal]Sark
[normal] Estate Management.  The word on the street, which I believe to be true but cannot verify, is that Mr Delaney ordered him to disregard his oath of office and keep him informed of all information that came his way or face being given the sack; he is no longer employed by SEM.  Another facet is that SEM discourage their staff from using the Island Hall and all their mail, other than for posting the 
[normal]Sark
[normal] Newsletter,
[normal]is taken to Guernsey to post rather than give work to the Island Post Office and this year SEM have withdrawn all their advertising of their hotels and other business in the 
[normal]Sark
[normal] Tourism Brochure and  have set up their own Tourist Office.  All the above makes the administration of 
[normal]Sark
[normal] difficult which I presume is their raison d’être and I find the assertion that it is due as much from Chief Pleas as from SEM difficult to understand.  
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]I have yet to witness any positive action made for the benefit of 
[normal]Sark
[normal], The nearest they ever came was in donating £200,000 towards the new Hall and School complex but in 2008 they 
[normal]took the trustees to court demanding their money be returned on the spurious grounds that they hadn’t realized the hall would have a bar.  Fortunately they lost or there would have been a few bankruptcies in 
[normal]Sark
[normal] that year.  Even their so called ‘inward investment’ in hotels is of little or no help as they have upgraded them beyond the means of the type of visitor who take holidays in 
[normal]Sark
[normal] and as a result once thriving, family run, hotels are ghosts of their former selves.  The vineyards may one day produce a little income for the Island but the cost is environmentally high for wild life, for visual enjoyment and for the considerable reduction of grazing for our farmers, shepherds and carriage owners. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]It is my view that the Barclays, after having failed to have 
[normal]Brecqhou
[normal] acknowledged as totally independent of 
[normal]Sark
[normal] have set their sights on 
[normal]Sark
[normal] itself, and after having been rejected in the polls are trying to ruin the governance and economy of the island.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]J M Beaumont   
[normal]Seigneur
[normal]cc.  
[normal]Rt
[normal] Hon Lord McNally
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]14 November 2013
